title: Grateful Dead Live at Fillmore West on 1970-06-05
description:
Set 1

Dire Wolf, I Know You Rider, Silver Threads, Friend Of The Devil, Me & My Uncle, Black Peter, New Speedway Boogie

Set 2

Cold Rain & Snow, Easy Wind, Mama Tried, Cryptical Envelopement-> Drums-> The Other One-> Cryptical Envelopement-> Attics Of My Life, Hard To Handle, It's A Man's World, Uncle John's Band, E:Saint Stephen-> E: Casey Jones

Other artist(s): GD; NRPS; Southern Comfort

reviews.review_text: Is that really an AUD? Is that really an audience recording? If so, wow.
Thank you. Sounds Excellent  !!! love the acoustic "I Know You Riders"

Poor Bear The band rides him mercilessly regarding various problems with the monitors.  First they can't hear themselves and then the drums are mic'd too loud.

Pipgen:  "There's not going to be another fucking word sung from the stage until the monitors get fixed."

Around 7:00 into the Other One there's some high pitched feedback (from the cymbals, sounds like) and you can hear Bobby scream "GODDAMMIT!"

But, as others have noted, the quality of this recording and transfer is amazing.  Personally, I find the sound of the band playing right at the bleeding edge of sonic overload most exciting (and it doesn't appear that this audience minded very much).  Plenty of detail here, with all the instruments nicely eq'd and separated.

The cut towards the end of Cryptical is brutal but it's a great version otherwise (the Attics barely exists on this tape).

Pig seems to be pretty fired up for this Hard to Handle.  There's a few warts in this version and it never really leaves the atmosphere but still a fine cruise.

The St. Stephen, on the other hand, includes an exceptionally intense, no-nonsense jam.  I'm sure Casey Jones was not what most people had in mind for a follow-up but it, too, is played with sharp focus and loads of energy.
- So many good shows from this era that even this nice clean "audience recording" is a bit beige in comparison.
Off the tracks.... ....Hard To Handle gets off rough, but smooths out like butter....nice

Audience recording? No.  Mic recording? Yes. Obviously this wasn't recorded from the audience, but there are telltale signs that this is a miced stage recording.  E.g., slight speaker boominess (an artifact of vibrations coming from the containing boxes themselves) that wouldn't show up on a straight SBD.  So while this is a mic recording, strictly speaking it's not AUD.  Then again, it ain't no stinkin' board, neither. ;-)
